============================
NameVerse API Documentation Blueprint
============================

Goal:
-----
Build a complete, SEO-friendly, live-testing API documentation frontend 
for the NameVerse API, WITHOUT using Next.js. The documentation should 
allow users to explore endpoints, test requests, and see limits on free vs paid API keys.

---

1. Core Tools
-------------
1. OpenAPI:
   - Standard format to describe API endpoints.
   - Includes paths, parameters, request/response bodies, authentication, and descriptions.
   - Your API spec file will be named `openapi.yaml`.

2. Redoc:
   - Tool that reads OpenAPI spec and generates interactive API documentation.
   - Supports live try-out of API calls.
   - Can be fully static (no backend needed).
   - SEO-friendly when hosted correctly.

3. Hosting:
   - Any static hosting platform works:
     - Vercel (recommended)
     - Netlify
     - GitHub Pages
   - Only requirement: `docs.html` and `openapi.yaml` are accessible via URL.

4. Alternative SSGs (Optional):
   - Docusaurus:
     - React-based static site generator.
     - Supports multiple docs pages, versioning, SEO.
     - Can integrate Redoc plugin to render API documentation.
   - VuePress / VitePress:
     - Vue-based SSG, lightweight, SEO-friendly.

---

2. File Structure (Minimal Static)
---------------------------------
/public
  ├─ openapi.yaml      # Your OpenAPI specification file
  └─ docs.html         # Redoc frontend HTML page

docs.html example:
-----------------
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>NameVerse API Documentation</title>
    <script src="https://cdn.redoc.ly/redoc/latest/bundles/redoc.standalone.js"></script>
  </head>
  <body>
    <redoc spec-url="/openapi.yaml" try-it-out-enabled></redoc>
  </body>
</html>

Notes:
- `try-it-out-enabled` allows live testing of API endpoints.
- `spec-url` points to your OpenAPI YAML file.

---

3. OpenAPI Spec Structure
-------------------------
- Define all endpoints, e.g.:

paths:
  /names/{religion}/{name}:
    get:
      summary: "Get name meaning by religion and name"
      parameters:
        - name: "religion"
          in: "path"
          required: true
          schema:
            type: string
        - name: "name"
          in: "path"
          required: true
          schema:
            type: string
      responses:
        200:
          description: "Successful response"
          content:
            application/json:
              schema:
                type: object
                properties:
                  name:
                    type: string
                  meaning:
                    type: string
                  origin:
                    type: string
      security:
        - apiKeyAuth: []

- Add authentication info:
components:
  securitySchemes:
    apiKeyAuth:
      type: apiKey
      in: header
      name: x-api-key

- You can also document limits:
  - Free tier: 1000 requests/day
  - Paid tier: unlimited requests

---

4. SEO and Google Indexing
--------------------------
- Add `robots.txt` pointing to your docs:
  User-agent: *
  Allow: /
  Sitemap: https://nameverse.vercel.app/sitemap.xml

- Optionally, generate a sitemap for all endpoints.
- Ensure Redoc HTML pages and YAML spec are accessible publicly.

---

5. Hosting & Deployment
----------------------
Option 1: Static HTML (Simplest)
- Upload `docs.html` + `openapi.yaml` to `/public` folder
- Deploy to Vercel, Netlify, or GitHub Pages
- Fully SEO-friendly and indexed by Google

Option 2: Docusaurus
- Install Docusaurus
- Integrate Redoc plugin
- Multi-page documentation with SEO + versioning
- Deploy as static site

---

6. Monetization
---------------
- Free usage with limited API key
- Paid API key for unlimited requests
- Optional ads or affiliate links in docs
- Display rate limits clearly in OpenAPI spec

---

7. Summary
----------
- **Core Stack**: OpenAPI + Redoc + Static Hosting
- **Optional Frameworks**: Docusaurus / VuePress for advanced documentation
- **Features**:
  - Live try-out
  - API limits
  - Free + Paid plans
  - SEO-friendly
  - Easy deployment (no Next.js required)

---

This blueprint ensures that you can start **building your API documentation** efficiently, 
host it online, allow live API testing, and make it SEO-friendly for indexing. 
You can scale it for multiple endpoints and even monetize API access.
